Hypothesis
We predict that seasons with higher pro meta diversity (lower hero pick rate concentration) will correlate positively with higher or growing monthly active player counts. Our reasoning is that a diverse meta signals a healthier, more accessible competitive environment, which increases spectator appeal and keeps casual players engaged with a broader pool of viable heroes. We also expect this effect to show a short lag of one to two weeks, as player behavior typically shifts shortly after a major tournament or balance patch rather than instantaneously.

Data
Ideal Dataset
The ideal dataset has two parallel time series aligned by Overwatch 2 season (roughly nine-week intervals):
Pro meta variable: Hero pick rates across all OWCS matches per season (heroes x matches x tournaments), from which we compute Shannon entropy as a scalar diversity score. Variables needed: hero name, number of picks, total maps played, tournament name, season, date. Ideally at least 30 seasons/sub-seasons of data covering OWL (2018–2023) and OWCS (2023–present), giving roughly 200+ tournament events.
Player count variable: Monthly active player estimates with at minimum season-level granularity, cross-platform if possible. Variables needed: month, estimated MAU, daily peak concurrents, platform if broken out.
Control variables: New hero release (binary), major balance patch (binary), season start/end (binary), major external competitive events (e.g., Marvel Rivals launch).
Ideally these data are stored in a flat CSV with one row per season-week, allowing time-series regression.
Real Datasets
Winston's Lab (winstonslab.com): Tracks OWL and OWCS hero pick rates by tournament going back to 2017. Data is available via the site's hero statistics pages and some historical exports. This is the primary source for pro meta diversity calculations. Variables include hero, match, map, pick/ban, team, and tournament. Free to access with some scraping required for bulk export.
Blizzard Official Hero Statistics (overwatch.blizzard.com/en-us/rates): Blizzard's own hero stats page tracks pick rates and win rates for every hero, updated with each patch, across PC, region, and rank tier. This gives ranked/casual pick rate data as a secondary variable. Access is free with no application needed; historical patch-level data requires scraping or community-maintained archives (e.g., OW2 Stats Discord). Blizzard
ActivePlayer.io / SteamCharts: Steam player counts average around 25,000 concurrent players with peaks reaching 60,000 during major updates and events, while cross-platform estimates from ActivePlayer capture a broader picture. SteamCharts data is directly accessible via API. ActivePlayer data requires manual collection or web scraping. IconEra
The real datasets fall short of the ideal in two ways: (1) Blizzard does not release official cross-platform MAU, so player count estimates remain third-party approximations with unknown error margins; (2) Winston's Lab data pre-OW2 uses a 6v6 format, creating a structural break in the series that requires careful handling or scope limitation to OW2 seasons only.

Ethics
A. Data Collection
[X] A.1 Informed consent: All data used is publicly available aggregated performance data. No individual player data is collected. No informed consent issues apply.
[X] A.2 Collection bias: SteamCharts captures PC players only and excludes consoles. ActivePlayer.io uses estimates rather than verified counts. We will note these limitations explicitly in any analysis and avoid overgeneralizing from Steam-only numbers to total player population.
[X] A.3 Limit PII exposure: All data is at the hero/match aggregate level. No personally identifiable player information is used.
[X] A.4 Downstream bias mitigation: No protected group data is collected or used. Not applicable for this project.
B. Data Storage
[X] B.1 Data security: All data is stored in a shared private GitHub repository with access limited to team members. No sensitive data requiring encryption.
[X] B.2 Right to be forgotten: Only aggregate public game data is stored. No individual user data is present, so this is not applicable.
[X] B.3 Data retention plan: Data and analysis files will be retained for the duration of the course and archived in the team's GitHub repository for reproducibility, then ownership transfers to team members individually.
C. Analysis
[X] C.1 Missing perspectives: Our analysis is limited to publicly observable game metrics. We do not consult Blizzard employees or pro players directly. We acknowledge that player count is influenced by many factors beyond meta diversity (new hero releases, marketing, competitor games), and we include control variables to partially account for this.
[X] C.2 Dataset bias: Third-party player count estimates carry unknown confidence intervals. The SteamCharts figures dramatically undercount the true player base because they exclude Battle.net, PlayStation, and Xbox users. We will use Steam data as a relative trend indicator rather than an absolute count, and will clearly label this distinction.
[X] C.3 Honest representation: All visualizations will include error ranges where applicable and will not imply causal claims from a correlational analysis.
[X] C.4 Privacy in analysis: No PII is present in our dataset.
[X] C.5 Auditability: All code will be version-controlled in GitHub, and data collection scripts will be documented so the analysis is fully reproducible.
D. Modeling
[X] D.1 Proxy discrimination: No demographic or protected variables are involved. Not applicable.
[X] D.2 Fairness across groups: Not applicable for this project.
[X] D.3 Metric selection: Shannon entropy as our diversity metric may weight rarely-played heroes differently than intended. We will test robustness using alternative concentration metrics (e.g., Herfindahl index, top-5 pick share) and report all.
[X] D.4 Explainability: Our model is a correlation/regression, fully interpretable. Coefficients will be reported with plain-language explanations.
[X] D.5 Communicate limitations: We will clearly state that correlation does not establish causation, that player count data is estimated, and that meta diversity is one of many factors driving player counts.
E. Deployment
This is an academic analysis project with no deployment. Items E.1–E.4 are not applicable.

